country.name: Ethiopia
country.overview: Ethiopia, in the Horn of Africa, is a rugged, landlocked country split by the Great Rift Valley. With archaeological finds dating back more than 3 million years, it’s a place of ancient culture. Among its important sites are Lalibela with its rock-cut Christian churches from the 12th–13th centuries. Aksum is the ruins of an ancient city with obelisks, tombs, castles and Our Lady Mary of Zion church.

translations.name: ประเทศเอธิโอเปีย

geography.area_note: slightly less than twice the size of Texas
geography.climate: tropical monsoon with wide topographic-induced variation
geography.terrain: high plateau with central mountain range divided by Great Rift Valley
geography.hazards: geologically active Great Rift Valley susceptible to earthquakes, volcanic eruptions; frequent droughts
geography.notes: landlocked - entire coastline along the Red Sea was lost with the de jure independence of Eritrea on 24 May 1993; Ethiopia is, therefore, the most populous landlocked country in the world; the Blue Nile, the chief headstream of the Nile by water volume, rises in T'ana Hayk (Lake Tana) in northwest Ethiopia; three major crops are believed to have originated in Ethiopia: coffee, grain sorghum, and castor bean
